    "πq Doing this for all active exponents and removing all the points d ∈ A ⊂ ∂ yields the fission surface that we denote by Σ = Σ(Θ), i.e. concretely we have",
    "where ⟨q 1 ⟩,.",
    ", ⟨q n ⟩ are the connected components of I.",
    "A fission local system on this fission surface consists of a local system V on Σ, a local system V i on any ⟨q i ⟩ × [0, ε], and for any connected component",
    "The V i define a local system on I × [0, ε], and since a local system on I is the same as an I-graded local system on ∂ × [0, ε], we see that a fission local system is nothing but a local system on Σ(Θ) graded by I on the halo H. In particular, any Stokes local system can naturally be regarded as a fission local system."
